    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a really solid starting point for them. I want to make sure they understand why it's such a powerful concept compared to just regular procedural due process. Can you add a section that shows why the \"substantive\" part is the real hero here for protecting rights, compared to just making sure the government follows the right steps or rules?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Procedural due process is merely about the *how*—ensuring fair hearings and proper procedures when the government acts. Substantive due process, however, is the *what*, because it judges whether the government action itself is fundamentally fair and respects core rights. It allows the courts to invalidate laws, even if passed through perfect procedures, if those laws violate basic human dignity. This is why it is the true engine for expanding civil liberties, not just a procedural checklist.",
      "source": "target",
