    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I've had some students ask about critics who say substantive due process is just \"judicial activism\" or that it lets judges make up rights that aren't actually in the Constitution. How should I address those viewpoints in my lesson without undermining the importance of the concept?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics who label substantive due process as \"judicial activism\" are fundamentally arguing against the very concept of a living Constitution. They fear that judges are imposing their personal policy preferences rather than interpreting fixed text. However, the Supreme Court has consistently shown that interpreting the Constitution requires discerning underlying principles of liberty, which is not the same as inventing rights. The concept is a necessary judicial check against legislative overreach, not a license for judicial fantasy.",
      "source": "target",
